  "steps": [
    {
      "id": "intro",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "The family",
      "body": "# The family\n\nHere is the core family vocabulary in Spanish:\n\n| Spanish | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| la familia | the family |\n| el padre | the father |\n| la madre | the mother |\n| el hermano | the brother |\n| la hermana | the sister |\n| el hijo | the son |\n| la hija | the daughter |\n| el abuelo | the grandfather |\n| la abuela | the grandmother |\n\nTwo important plurals:\n\n- **los padres** = the **parents** (not just the fathers)\n- **los abuelos** = the **grandparents** (not just the grandfathers)\n\nIn Spanish the masculine plural form covers a mixed group."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-possessive",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "Possessive adjectives",
      "body": "## mi, tu, su, nuestro\n\n| Singular | Plural | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| **mi** | **mis** | my |\n| **tu** | **tus** | your |\n| **su** | **sus** | his / her / your / their |\n| **nuestro / nuestra** | **nuestros / nuestras** | our |\n\n**Key point — agreement is with the NOUN, not with the owner.**\n\n- mi, tu, su agree only with the **number** of the noun:\n  - *mi hermano* (singular) -> *mis hermanos* (plural)\n  - *su casa* -> *sus casas*\n- nuestro agrees with both **number AND gender** of the noun:\n  - *nuestro hijo* (m. sg.) / *nuestra hija* (f. sg.)\n  - *nuestros hijos* (m. pl.) / *nuestras hijas* (f. pl.)\n\nRemember: *mis hermanos* means **my** brothers — the *mis* says nothing about whether I am male or female. It only matches *hermanos* (plural)."
    },
    {
      "id": "step-su",
      "type": "theory",
      "title": "The ambiguous su",
      "body": "## su can mean many things\n\nThe form **su** is ambiguous. *su casa* can mean:\n\n- **his** house\n- **her** house\n- **your** house (formal, from usted)\n- **their** house\n\nContext makes clear who is meant:\n\n- *Maria habla con su madre.* — Maria talks to **her** mother.\n- *Pedro busca su libro.* — Pedro looks for **his** book.\n\nIf it is genuinely unclear, you can spell it out: *la casa **de el*** (his) / *la casa **de ella*** (her).\n\nAnd don't forget: before a plural noun *su* becomes **sus** — *sus padres* = his/her/their parents."
    },
